SIMPLE: nativity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nativity
<hw>Na*tiv"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Nativies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F.
<ets>nativit⟦eacute⟧</ets>, L. <ets>nativitas</ets>. See
<er>Native</er>, and cf. <er>Na⟦ium⟧vet⟦eacute⟧</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The coming into life or into the world; birth; also, the
circumstances attending birth, as time, place, manner, etc.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have served him from the hour of my <qex>nativity</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou hast left . . . the land of thy <qex>nativity</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Ruth ii. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These in their dark <qex>nativity</qex> the deep⟦br⟧
Shall yield us, pregnant with infernal flame.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <mark>(capitalized)</mark> <def>A
picture representing or symbolizing the early infancy of Christ. The
simplest form is the babe in a rude cradle, and the heads of an ox and
an ass to express the stable in which he was born.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Astrol.)</fld> <def>A representation of the
positions of the heavenly bodies as the moment of one's birth, supposed
to indicate one's future destinies; a horoscope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The Nativity</b></col>, <cd>the birth or birthday of
Christ; Christmas day.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To cast one's
nativity</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To calculate one's
nativity</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Astrol.)</fld>, <cd>to find out and
represent the position of the heavenly bodies at the time of one's
birth.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Natka</ent>⟦br⟧
